  "text": "Grafana's configuration loading system is implemented primarily in the pkg/setting package. The system uses the gopkg.in/ini.v1 library for parsing INI configuration files.\n\n**INI File Parsing and Loading:**\nThe configuration is loaded in pkg/setting/setting.go through the Cfg struct and loadConfiguration method. The system loads a defaults.ini file from conf/defaults.ini, followed by custom configuration files. The loaded INI file is stored in Cfg.Raw as an *ini.File structure.\n\n**Environment Variable Override Logic:**\nEnvironment variable overrides are applied through the applyEnvVariableOverrides method (pkg/setting/setting.go:744) which iterates through all sections and keys in the INI file, checking for corresponding environment variables using the EnvKey function. The EnvKey function (pkg/setting/setting.go:855) constructs environment variable names in the format GF_SECTION_KEY (e.g., GF_SECURITY_ADMIN_PASSWORD for the admin_password setting in the security section). Environment variables take precedence over file-based configuration.\n\nThe DynamicSection struct (pkg/setting/setting.go:1568) provides dynamic environment variable overrides at access time, with the SectionWithEnvOverrides method allowing settings to be overridden with environment variables even after initialization. The Key method in DynamicSection checks for environment variable overrides before returning a configuration value.\n\n**Default Values per Section:**\nDefault values are defined in the conf/defaults.ini file which is loaded first in the configuration chain. The defaults are merged with custom configuration and environment overrides. Each section (like [security], [paths], [auth], etc.) in the INI file defines the default values for its respective configuration options.\n\n**Configuration Variable Expansion:**\nThe expandConfig function (pkg/setting/expanders.go:52) handles expansion of configuration values containing environment variables and file references. It uses a plugin-based Expander interface (pkg/setting/expanders.go:13) with implementations for:\n- envExpander (pkg/setting/expanders.go:114): Expands ${VAR_NAME} syntax to environment variable values\n- fileExpander (pkg/setting/expanders.go:132): Reads file contents for values specified as file paths\n\nThe regex pattern $(|__\\w+){([^}]+)} matches expandable values, allowing syntax like $(ENV_VAR) or $__file(/path/to/file).\n\n**Sensitive Configuration Value Masking:**\nThe RedactedValue function (pkg/setting/setting.go:660) masks sensitive configuration values for the /api/admin/settings endpoint. It detects sensitive keys using pattern matching against patterns like \"PASSWORD\", \"SECRET\", \"PRIVATE_KEY\", \"CERTIFICATE\", \"TOKEN\", \"API_KEY\", etc., and returns a masked value (\"*********\") for these keys. URLs containing credentials are masked using the RedactedURL function (pkg/setting/setting.go:711) which redacts passwords and usernames from URLs while preserving the rest of the URL structure.\n\nThe admin settings endpoint is implemented in pkg/api/admin.go. The AdminGetSettings handler (line 29) calls hs.getAuthorizedSettings which filters the settings based on user permissions through access control evaluation. The settings returned by SettingsProvider.Current() (pkg/setting/provider.go:118) are already redacted through the OSSImpl implementation, which applies RedactedValue to each configuration value before returning it in the SettingsBag.\n\n**Configuration Loading Chain:**\nThe complete configuration loading chain is: loadConfiguration -> load defaults.ini -> apply command-line overrides -> load custom configuration -> applyEnvVariableOverrides -> expandConfig -> SettingsProvider.Current() with RedactedValue masking -> AdminGetSettings endpoint with access control filtering."
}

